avy social upheaval. Nothing is consistent, nothing is stable, and thus nothing is sound. The incredible and vast use of sound proves their wish for a stable society and a consistent, happy life. Furthermore, sound can be related to this wish for safety by its use for explaining noise and warnings. This negative side to sound likely reflects this need for warning danger present in their current society. Constant noise and destruction led to the use of having to 'sound' the alarms or even categorize this constant noise as sound. Overall, the Nacirema people are devastated people, desperately clinging to the long-lost idea of stability and facing their destruction-filled reality through the use of sound. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: E:)%0a%3c (:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
